{"id":"2210.04928","submitter":"Stanislav Nikitin","authors":"Tao Xie, A. A. Eberharter, Jie Xing, S. Nishimoto, M. Brando, P.\n  Khanenko, J. Sichelschmidt, A. A. Turrini, D. G. Mazzone, P. G. Naumov, L. D.\n  Sanjeewa, N. Harrison, A. S. Sefat, B. Normand, A. M. Lauchli, A. Podlesnyak,\n  S. E. Nikitin","title":"Complete field-induced spectral response of the spin-1/2\n  triangular-lattice antiferromagnet CsYbSe$_2$","comments":"10 + 13 pages, 4 + 15 Figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.str-el","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Fifty years after Anderson's proposal of the resonating valence-bond state,\nthe spin-1/2 triangular-lattice Heisenberg antiferromagnet (TLHAF) remains\nperhaps the ultimate platform to explore highly entangled quantum spin states\nin proximity to magnetic order. Yb-based delafossites are ideal candidate TLHAF\nmaterials, displaying strong two-dimensionality, pseudospin-1/2 nature and no\nstructural disorder. We report a systematic neutron scattering study of\nCsYbSe$_2$ over the full range of applied in-plane magnetic fields up to\nsaturation. Above saturation we establish the exact Heisenberg character of the\ninteractions and a weak second-neighbour coupling, $J_2/J_1 \\simeq 0.03$. As\nthe field drives the system from the 120$^{\\circ}$-ordered state through the\nup-up-down phase around 1/3-magnetization and towards full polarization, the\ncorresponding excitation spectra evolve from continuum-like to relatively sharp\nspin-wave modes in the up-up-down phase, then back to continua and back to spin\nwaves. We perform cylinder MPS calculations based on the $J_1$-$J_2$ Heisenberg\nmodel that reproduce the experimental spectra with semi-quantitative accuracy,\nsuggesting an interpretation of the extensive continuum features in terms of\nmulti-magnon states. Thus our comprehensive experimental and theoretical\nanalysis of the unconventional field-induced spin excitations in the TLHAF\nprovides valuable insight into the dynamics of a broad class of quantum\nmany-body systems.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 10 Oct 2022 18:01:08 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 18 Oct 2022 14:03:20 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-10-19"}
{"id":"2210.04929","submitter":"Geoffrey Ramseyer","authors":"Geoffrey Ramseyer, Mohak Goyal, Ashish Goel, David Mazi\\`eres","title":"Batch Exchanges with Constant Function Market Makers: Axioms,\n  Equilibria, and Computation","comments":"24 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.GT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Batch trading systems and constant function market makers (CFMMs) are two\ndistinct market design innovations that have recently come to prominence as\nways to address some of the shortcomings of decentralized trading systems.\nHowever, different deployments have chosen substantially different methods for\nintegrating the two innovations.\n  We show here from a minimal set of axioms describing the beneficial\nproperties of each innovation that there is in fact only one, unique method for\nintegrating CFMMs into batch trading schemes that preserves all the beneficial\nproperties of both. Deployment of a batch trading schemes trading many assets\nsimultaneously requires a reliable algorithm for approximating equilibria in\nArrow-Debreu exchange markets. We study this problem when batches contain limit\norders and CFMMs. Specifically, we find that CFMM design affects the asymptotic\ncomplexity of the problem, give an easily-checkable criterion to validate that\na user-submitted CFMM is computationally tractable in a batch, and give a\nconvex program that computes equilibria on batches of limit orders and CFMMs.\nEquivalently, this convex program computes equilibria of Arrow-Debreu exchange\nmarkets when every agent's demand response satisfies weak gross\nsubstitutability and every agent has utility for only two types of assets. This\nconvex program has rational solutions when run on many (but not all) natural\nclasses of widely-deployed CFMMs.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 10 Oct 2022 18:02:18 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 14 Oct 2022 20:42:35 GMT"},{"ver