{"id":"2210.05235","submitter":"Felix Christian Clemen","authors":"Felix Christian Clemen and Emily Heath and Mikhail Lavrov","title":"Online Ramsey numbers of ordered paths and cycles","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  An ordered graph is a graph with a linear ordering on its vertices. The\nonline Ramsey game for ordered graphs $G$ and $H$ is played on an infinite\nsequence of vertices; on each turn, Builder draws an edge between two vertices,\nand Painter colors it red or blue. Builder tries to create a red $G$ or a blue\n$H$ as quickly as possible, while Painter wants the opposite. The online\nordered Ramsey number $r_o(G,H)$ is the number of turns the game lasts with\noptimal play.\n  In this paper, we consider the behavior of $r_o(G,P_n)$ for fixed $G$, where\n$P_n$ is the monotone ordered path. We prove an $O(n \\log n)$ bound on\n$r_o(G,P_n)$ for all $G$ and an $O(n)$ bound when $G$ is $3$-ichromatic; we\npartially classify graphs $G$ with $r_o(G,P_n) = n + O(1)$. Many of these\nresults extend to $r_o(G,C_n)$, where $C_n$ is an ordered cycle obtained from\n$P_n$ by adding one edge.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 11 Oct 2022 08:05:56 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-10-12"}
